  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Fair trade for African Blackwood: achieving self-sufficiency - phase 1</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Rare and valuable hardwoods such as African Blackwood are uniquely suited to making expensive musical instruments. However, the communities in Tanzania living in and around forests containing African Blackwood have average annual household incomes of less than US$300. Environment Africa Trust supports communities to collectively manage their forests and link up with the Forestry Stewardship Council to certify them. They support communities to maintain their current certifications and manage new revenues they receive from their certified wood sales. They also facilitate the certification of new communities. They engage directly with key companies in the supply chain, including loggers and sawmills, music manufacturers and distributors. They also work to create the demand amongst musicians for instruments made from sustainable and certified Blackwood and put pressure on companies to avoid buying illegally logged hardwoods. As a result, local people gain a more sustainable income from forest products and there is greater awareness amongst consumers of ethical sourcing of woodwind instruments.</narrative>
  </description>
